Deep vein thrombosis (#DVT) is a blood clot formed inside larger vein, usually deep within lower leg or thigh breaking off into bloodstream.
#DVT strikes 1/2 million Americans, claims 100K every year. Symptoms: redness, swelling, tenderness or pain in clot area, usually lower leg.
Clot loose in bloodstream can block supply to lungs called pulmonary embolism. Symptoms: trouble breathing, low BP, and chest pain. #DVT
#DVT causes: damage to inner lining of veins incl surgery, injury or immune system resposnse, genetic disorder, hormone change and idleness
#DVT risk factors include cancer, surgery, extended bed rest, aging, smoking, obesity, pregnancy, childbirth, and hormonal contraception.

Up to 5% of Pts with arm #DVT will have PE, 20% post-thrombotic syndrome, about 8% will have recurrence of their arm DVT later if untreated.
Acute arm #DVT comprise minority of DVTs <10%, about 3/4 are considered provoked by central venous catheters, pacemakers or malignancy.
ACCP advises when a CV catheter is responsible for acute #DVT & central line is not needed or is not working, it should be removed Grade 2C
When CV catheter is causing acute #DVT,If there is reason to keep it,anticoagulation & continuing to use line is appropriate Grade 2C #ACCP
ACCP, treat arm acute DVTs with full anticoagulation when #DVT involves axillary/more proximal veins Grade 1B
For arm acute #DVT, ACCP suggests using LMWH (enoxaparin, dalteparin or tinzaparin) or fondaparinux rather than IV or SQ heparin Grade 2B/2C
Asymptomatic brachial #DVT, do serial exam & US for extension to axillary or therapeutic for < 3 months or prophylactic anticoagulation
Unprovoked upper extremity #DVT in proximal veins (axillary/more proximal), ACCP recommends 3 months of anticoagulation & no more. Grade 1B
Pts with arm #DVT secondary to CV catheter that was removed, 3 months of anticoagulation Grade 1B, even if they also have cancer Grade 2C
For patients with cancer and an arm #DVT (but no central line), #ACCP doesn‚Äôt make an explicit recommendation.
Full anticoagulation for isolated brachial vein #DVT if causing symptoms,associated with cancer or central line that will remain #ACCP
